o consider the practical impact the instrument will have. What are the specific challenges from the point of view of politics, society, the judiciary, and academia? For instance, does a European sales pose a threat to Member States' codifications of civil law as symbols of national sovereignty? What are the potential benefits of a further sales regime, in addition to national law and the CISG? How can national courts keep track of it? Do the contracting parties really have a choice, as the "blue button"-concept suggests? How can a further sales regime be integrated into the academic curriculum? The book "COMMON EUROPEAN SALES LAW MEETS REALITY" tries to answer these important questions. It is addressed to legal practitioners, teachers, researchers and students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConflict of lawsxCongressesxSalesxEuropean Union countries. 0aConflict of lawsxSaleszEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 0aSalesxCongressesxEuropean Union countriesxEuropexEuropean Union countries. 0aSaleszEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 4aEuropäisches Privatrecht. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aAardweg, Willem van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAncel, Pascal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHöland, Armin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKull, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehmann, Matthias, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMackie, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartínez Velencoso, Luz María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMistelis, Loukas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidt-Kessel, Martin